<div n="a" type="textpart" subtype="fragment"><ab>  <lb n="0"/><gap reason="lost" unit="character" quantity="3"/>  <lb n="1"/> <w lemma="χαίρω">χαῖρε</w></ab></div><div n="b" type="textpart" subtype="fragment"><ab>   <lb n="1"/> <orig n="unresolved">α<unclear reason="damage">ιι</unclear></orig> <space extent="3" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>  </ab></div><div n="c" type="textpart" subtype="fragment"><ab>   <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Μηνόδοτος"><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">Μη</supplied>νόδοτος</name></persName>  <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Ἀλέξανδρος"><supplied reason="lost">Ἀ</supplied><unclear reason="damage">λ</unclear>εξάνδρου</name></persName>  <lb n="3"/><w><gap reason="lost" unit="character" quantity="1"/>ιος</w> <w lemma="χαίρω">χαῖρε</w> </ab></div>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p> a: <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/> farewell. c: Menodotos, son of Alexandros <gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/> farewell</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>I take the first word in l. 3 to be probably a second name for ?Menodotos; its first letter is lost, the second has a horizontal on the base line, but is almost certainly not Δ: e.g. Ἀσιος vel. sim. The traces do not accord with any of the epithets which commonly appear in this position in epitaphs - e.g. ἀώρος, χρῆστος; and in any case these would normally be in the vocative.</p>
         </div>
